unveil the Pampa's mystery.

00:26:01.440 --> 00:26:04.910 align:middle line:90%


00:26:04.910 --> 00:26:09.020 align:middle line:84%
And the enigmatic figure traced
on the side of a small hill

00:26:09.020 --> 00:26:12.390 align:middle line:84%
seems to look and salute
someone in flight.

00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:14.900 align:middle line:84%
But who flew in
the distant past?

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:19.610 align:middle line:90%


00:26:19.610 --> 00:26:23.580 align:middle line:84%
A plot which thickens even
more over the past few years

00:26:23.580 --> 00:26:26.220 align:middle line:84%
with the discovery of other
drawings and geometric

00:26:26.220 --> 00:26:29.992 align:middle line:84%
figures in the close
by Palpa Plain.

00:26:29.992 --> 00:26:33.359 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:26:33.359 --> 00:26:34.810 align:middle line:90%


00:26:34.810 --> 00:26:36.850 align:middle line:84%
The style is similar
to the Nazca,

00:26:36.850 --> 00:26:39.490 align:middle line:84%
but these date
further back in time

00:26:39.490 --> 00:26:41.500 align:middle line:84%
and are still only
comprehensible

00:26:41.500 --> 00:26:43.350 align:middle line:90%
from above in flight.

00:26:43.350 --> 00:26:46.250 align:middle line:90%


00:26:46.250 --> 00:26:48.950 align:middle line:84%
Finally, the Nazca
and Palpa drawings

00:26:48.950 --> 00:26:53.030 align:middle line:84%
cover a total area of nearly
600 square kilometers,

00:26:53.030 --> 00:26:57.200 align:middle line:84%
and to be created, thousands
of tons of stones were shifted.

00:26:57.200 --> 00:27:00.960 align:middle line:90%


00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:04.150 align:middle line:84%
Only a very important
reason could justify

00:27:04.150 --> 00:27:06.360 align:middle line:90%
any activity of this magnitude.

00:27:06.360 --> 00:27:09.811 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:27:09.811 --> 00:27:17.220 align:middle line:90%


00:27:17.220 --> 00:27:21.330 align:middle line:84%
The Antonini Educational
Museum is in the town of Nazca,

00:27:21.330 --> 00:27:24.180 align:middle line:84%
where many archaeological
finds of the Nazca culture

00:27:24.180 --> 00:27:26.670 align:middle line:84%
are kept, the last
to have inhabited

00:27:26.670 --> 00:27:29.760 align:middle line:84%
this land before the Incas,
who incorporated them

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:32.850 align:middle line:84%
into their empire, canceling
out all their customs

00:27:32.850 --> 00:27:34.970 align:middle line:90%
and traditions.

00:27:34.970 --> 00:27:37.760 align:middle line:84%
The Nazca had reached an
incredible artistic and

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:41.240 align:middle line:84%
cultural level witnessed
by the exquisitely painted

00:27:41.240 --> 00:27:44.510 align:middle line:84%
ceramic wear and by the
sophisticated and efficient

00:27:44.510 --> 00:27:48.270 align:middle line:84%
underground aqueduct
system they had built.

00:27:48.270 --> 00:27:50.700 align:middle line:84%
There are no elements
in these finds which

00:27:50.700 --> 00:27:53.370 align:middle line:84%
help clarify the
mystery of the origins

00:27:53.370 --> 00:27:55.020 align:middle line:84%
and the significance
of the drawings

00:27:55.020 --> 00:28:00.990 align:middle line:84%
of the plain except
for one engraved

00:28:00.990 --> 00:28:04.110 align:middle line:90%
stone found in the Nazca Tomb.

00:28:04.110 --> 00:28:06.990 align:middle line:84%
The workmanship is not as
accurate as that of the Ica

00:28:06.990 --> 00:28:09.960 align:middle line:84%
stones, and the
drawings depict elements

00:28:09.960 --> 00:28:13.780 align:middle line:84%
ascribable to the
daily Nazca world.

00:28:13.780 --> 00:28:16.840 align:middle line:10%
But why would the
Nazca engrave stones

00:28:16.840 --> 00:28:20.080 align:middle line:10%
when they were perfectly
capable of painting exquisitely

00:28:20.080 --> 00:28:22.540 align:middle line:10%
colorful ceramic
wear and weaving

00:28:22.540 --> 00:28:25.300 align:middle line:10%
finely embroidered blankets?

00:28:25.300 --> 00:28:27.160 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps it was a
way of responding

00:28:27.160 --> 00:28:28.930 align:middle line:84%
to what they had
seen in finds they

00:28:28.930 --> 00:28:34.370 align:middle line:84%
believed to be of great
importance like the Ica stones.

00:28:34.370 --> 00:28:37.490 align:middle line:84%
Once again, the
engraved stones, which

00:28:37.490 --> 00:28:41.150 align:middle line:84%
were considered stones
of power, reappear.

00:28:41.150 --> 00:28:46.580 align:middle line:84%
Or were they, perhaps,
even stones of knowledge?

00:28:46.580 --> 00:28:50.460 align:middle line:84%
Is there a true connection
between the Ica and the Nazca?

00:28:50.460 --> 00:28:55.910 align:middle line:84%
A 1586 report written by a
magistrate, Luis de Monzón,

00:28:55.910 --> 00:28:59.180 align:middle line:84%
explained what the plains
natives said about the origins

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:00.620 align:middle line:90%
of the drawings.

00:29:00.620 --> 00:29:04.010 align:middle line:84%
During extremely ancient
times, a small group of people

00:29:04.010 --> 00:29:07.400 align:middle line:84%
called Viracochas, who
differed from the Indios,

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:09.470 align:middle line:84%
reached this land,
and the Indios

00:29:09.470 --> 00:29:12.890 align:middle line:84%
obeyed them, followed
them, and realized roads

00:29:12.890 --> 00:29:16.770 align:middle line:90%
which can still be seen today.

00:29:16.770 --> 00:29:19.790 align:middle line:10%
The Viracochas suddenly
left, but promised

00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:23.600 align:middle line:10%
to return, a memory and a
promise which was kept so alive

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:26.660 align:middle line:10%
in those people to deceive
the Incas and Aztecs when

00:29:26.660 --> 00:29:29.690 align:middle line:10%
they met the conquistadores
for the first time.

00:29:29.690 --> 00:29:33.380 align:middle line:84%
The Spanish were exchanged
for the gods who had returned,

00:29:33.380 --> 00:29:37.460 align:middle line:84%
thus allowing a handful of men
to defeat well-trained and much

00:29:37.460 --> 00:29:40.410 align:middle line:90%
more powerful armies.

00:29:40.410 --> 00:29:45.660 align:middle line:84%
But truthfully, who were the
Viracochas, a myth, a legend,

00:29:45.660 --> 00:29:47.940 align:middle line:90%
or a historical truth?

00:29:47.940 --> 00:29:51.120 align:middle line:84%
Were they the true inspirers
of the great civilizations

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:52.470 align:middle line:90%
of the past?

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:54.570 align:middle line:84%
Could the gods be
the survivors of

00:29:54.570 --> 00:29:57.870 align:middle line:84%
a remote and forgotten
civilization which

00:29:57.870 --> 00:30:01.740 align:middle line:84%
had reached a level of progress
equal to, or higher than,

00:30:01.740 --> 00:30:03.270 align:middle line:90%
the current one?

00:30:03.270 --> 00:30:06.540 align:middle line:84%
The Monzón chronicle and
the engraved stone exhibited

00:30:06.540 --> 00:30:09.090 align:middle line:84%
at the Antonini
Museum add a new,

00:30:09.090 --> 00:30:11.670 align:middle line:84%
important detail
to the other clues,

00:30:11.670 --> 00:30:15.210 align:middle line:84%
and the ancient oral traditions
seem increasingly less

00:30:15.210 --> 00:30:18.700 align:middle line:84%
of a myth, of a legend,
to become history.

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:21.320 align:middle line:90%


00:30:21.320 --> 00:30:24.230 align:middle line:84%
The Marcahuasi
Meseta lies on top

00:30:24.230 --> 00:30:29.780 align:middle line:84%
of a 4,200 meter mountain 80
kilometers northeast of Lima.

00:30:29.780 --> 00:30:33.290 align:middle line:84%
It is little known still
today, also because in order

00:30:33.290 --> 00:30:37.250 align:middle line:84%
to reach it, one has to organize
a true expedition rather

00:30:37.250 --> 00:30:38.880 align:middle line:90%
than a small trip.

00:30:38.880 --> 00:30:40.970 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the final
section of the road

00:30:40.970 --> 00:30:44.540 align:middle line:84%
to reach San Pedro de Casta,
the last inhabited center

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:47.390 align:middle line:84%
of the Meseta Valley,
is a mule track,

00:30:47.390 --> 00:30:50.120 align:middle line:84%
which clambers up the sides
of the mountain for about

00:30:50.120 --> 00:30:55.520 align:middle line:84%
30 kilometers, large
enough for a car to pass.

00:30:55.520 --> 00:30:57.980 align:middle line:84%
Driving along the road
at night without a guide

00:30:57.980 --> 00:31:01.060 align:middle line:84%
who knows the place is an
even more difficult task.

00:31:01.060 --> 00:31:03.930 align:middle line:90%


00:31:03.930 --> 00:31:06.260 align:middle line:84%
In fact, a five hour
trip is required

00:31:06.260 --> 00:31:11.330 align:middle line:84%
to reach the small
pueblo 3,200 meters up.

00:31:11.330 --> 00:31:13.790 align:middle line:10%
Mass tourism with
its comforts has not

00:31:13.790 --> 00:31:15.980 align:middle line:10%
yet spoiled the
primitive territory

00:31:15.980 --> 00:31:18.320 align:middle line:10%
surrounding the plateau.

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:22.550 align:middle line:10%
Marcahuasi was discovered by the
Peruvian archaeologist Daniel

00:31:22.550 --> 00:31:25.940 align:middle line:10%
Ruzo de los Heros in the '50s.

00:31:25.940 --> 00:31:27.800 align:middle line:84%
His research convinced
him that there

00:31:27.800 --> 00:31:30.170 align:middle line:84%
were some entrances to
the mythical network

00:31:30.170 --> 00:31:32.270 align:middle line:84%
of underground
tunnels which cross

00:31:32.270 --> 00:31:35.240 align:middle line:84%
South America and the
ruins of sculptures

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:39.470 align:middle line:84%
realized in a distant era by an
unknown and extremely evolved

00:31:39.470 --> 00:31:43.100 align:middle line:84%
population, which
he called Masma.

00:31:43.100 --> 00:31:46.490 align:middle line:84%
Could it be another trace of
the passage of the mythical

00:31:46.490 --> 00:31:49.850 align:middle line:90%
Viracochas?

00:31:49.850 --> 00:31:52.460 align:middle line:84%
In the small San
Pedro de Casta museum,

00:31:52.460 --> 00:31:56.960 align:middle line:84%
there are many meseta
finds discovered by Ruzo.

00:31:56.960 --> 00:31:58.940 align:middle line:84%
They come from a
settlement of Incas,

00:31:58.940 --> 00:32:02.030 align:middle line:84%
who lived in Marcahuasi long
before the disappearance

00:32:02.030 --> 00:32:04.880 align:middle line:90%
of the mysterious Masma culture.

00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:08.570 align:middle line:84%
Amongst the various types
of finds the mummies

00:32:08.570 --> 00:32:11.480 align:middle line:84%
with their facial
expressions paralyzed

00:32:11.480 --> 00:32:13.010 align:middle line:90%
in a moment of eternal terror.

00:32:13.010 --> 00:32:15.680 align:middle line:90%


00:32:15.680 --> 00:32:18.590 align:middle line:84%
Perhaps they are the
vestiges of Inca prisoners

00:32:18.590 --> 00:32:22.110 align:middle line:84%
tortured during the
Spanish conquest.

00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:24.060 align:middle line:90%
But this is not a certainty.

00:32:24.060 --> 00:32:27.560 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:32:27.560 --> 00:32:32.880 align:middle line:90%


00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:36.370 align:middle line:84%
The unpaved, small
square of San Pedro

00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:39.400 align:middle line:84%
is from where visitors to
the plateau usually depart.

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:42.816 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:32:42.816 --> 00:32:45.750 align:middle line:90%


00:32:45.750 --> 00:32:49.080 align:middle line:84%
The path leading to Marcahuasi
is even more difficult

00:32:49.080 --> 00:32:51.540 align:middle line:84%
than the one departing
from the valley.

00:32:51.540 --> 00:32:55.260 align:middle line:84%
It can only be covered by foot
or with pack animals, which

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:59.280 align:middle line:84%
become even more indispensable
when heavy, cumbersome luggage

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:01.620 align:middle line:84%
needs to be transported
to the meseta

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:04.211 align:middle line:90%
at an altitude of 4,000 meters.

00:33:04.211 --> 00:33:07.578 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:33:07.578 --> 00:33:12.400 align:middle line:90%


00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:15.070 align:middle line:10%
From one of the highest
points, the first ruins

00:33:15.070 --> 00:33:16.720 align:middle line:10%
of the ancient
Inca settlement can

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:22.240 align:middle line:10%
be seen, while further
on, there are even more.

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:24.310 align:middle line:10%
The meseta, in
fact, takes its name

00:33:24.310 --> 00:33:28.180 align:middle line:10%
from these ruins, one of
the few Inca constructions

00:33:28.180 --> 00:33:31.000 align:middle line:10%
to be built on two
inhabitable floors.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:35.280 align:middle line:84%
And the name "Marcahuasi" means
exactly "home with two floors."

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:40.000 align:middle line:90%


00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:42.990 align:middle line:84%
Daniel Ruzo de los Heros
has studied the ruins

00:33:42.990 --> 00:33:45.450 align:middle line:84%
of the meseta for
eight years in a row,

00:33:45.450 --> 00:33:48.556 align:middle line:84%
stationing at the plateau
for six months a year.

00:33:48.556 --> 00:33:51.958 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:33:51.958 --> 00:33:55.360 align:middle line:90%


00:33:55.360 --> 00:33:57.950 align:middle line:84%
The small heart where the
archaeologist would camp

00:33:57.950 --> 00:34:01.840 align:middle line:84%
is still in an excellent
state and an obliged stopover

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:03.790 align:middle line:90%
for anyone visiting Marcahuasi.

00:34:03.790 --> 00:34:07.206 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:34:07.206 --> 00:34:10.630 align:middle line:90%


00:34:10.630 --> 00:34:13.239 align:middle line:84%
Manuel Olivares is
an expert guide who

00:34:13.239 --> 00:34:16.560 align:middle line:90%
knows the meseta inside out.

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:19.620 align:middle line:84%
He accompanied [? Ruzo ?]
during the last years, when

00:34:19.620 --> 00:34:22.320 align:middle line:84%
the archaeologists studied
the Marcahuasi sculptures

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:23.730 align:middle line:90%
and cavities.

00:34:23.730 --> 00:34:26.489 align:middle line:84%
Even today, Don
Manuel acts as a guide

00:34:26.489 --> 00:34:29.100 align:middle line:84%
to the very few
tourists and researchers

00:34:29.100 --> 00:34:31.692 align:middle line:90%
who adventure to the meseta.

00:34:31.692 --> 00:34:34.660 align:middle line:10%
